About the iris Dataset¶

Description

The dataset contains measurements of four features (variables) for 150 iris flowers from three different species (classes).

Variable definitions

  • Sepal Length (cm): The length of the sepal of the flower.
  • Sepal Width (cm): The width of the sepal of the flower.
  • Petal Length (cm): The length of the petal of the flower.
  • Petal Width (cm): The width of the petal of the flower.
  • Species: The species of the iris flower which is the target class

Check for normality using Shapiro-Wilk test:¶

We use the Shapiro-Wilk test to check for normality in each variable.

If the p-value is greater than 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the variable follows a normal distribution.

In [ ]:
# Check for normality using Shapiro-Wilk test
print("\nChecking for normality...")
for col in Iris.columns[:-1]:  # Exclude the Species column
    stat, p = shapiro(Iris[col])
    print(f"Shapiro-Wilk test for {col}: stat={stat:.2f}, p={p:.2f}")
    if p > 0.05:
        print(f"{col} follows a normal distribution (fail to reject H0)")
    else:
        print(f"{col} does not follow a normal distribution (reject H0)")

Checking for normality...
Shapiro-Wilk test for Sepal.Length: stat=0.98, p=0.01
Sepal.Length does not follow a normal distribution (reject H0)
Shapiro-Wilk test for Sepal.Width: stat=0.98, p=0.10
Sepal.Width follows a normal distribution (fail to reject H0)
Shapiro-Wilk test for Petal.Length: stat=0.88, p=0.00
Petal.Length does not follow a normal distribution (reject H0)
Shapiro-Wilk test for Petal.Width: stat=0.90, p=0.00
Petal.Width does not follow a normal distribution (reject H0)

Normality Test:¶

The Shapiro-Wilk test checks if the variables follow a normal distribution.

In [ ]:
# 6. Perform the Shapiro-Wilk test for normality on each of the quantitative variables
print("\nShapiro-Wilk Test for Normality:")
for var in variables:
    stat, p = shapiro(Iris[var])
    print(f'\n{var}: Statistics={stat}, p-value={p}')
    if p > 0.05:
        print(f'{var} looks Gaussian (fail to reject H0)')
    else:
        print(f'{var} does not look Gaussian (reject H0)')

Shapiro-Wilk Test for Normality:

Sepal.Length: Statistics=0.9760902723490532, p-value=0.010181161454691156
Sepal.Length does not look Gaussian (reject H0)

Sepal.Width: Statistics=0.9849178695056319, p-value=0.10115426916130282
Sepal.Width looks Gaussian (fail to reject H0)

Petal.Length: Statistics=0.8762680554631075, p-value=7.412263135173186e-10
Petal.Length does not look Gaussian (reject H0)

Petal.Width: Statistics=0.9018349381915991, p-value=1.680465210314913e-08
Petal.Width does not look Gaussian (reject H0)

The Shapiro-Wilk Test is meant to check the null hypothesis that the data was got from a normal distribution.¶

P-values of Sepal.Length, Petal.Length, and Petal.Width are less than 0.05, therefore, it is not true that they are not normally distributed. The P-value of Sepal.Width is greater than 0.05 meaning it is normally distributed.¶

One-way ANOVA Test:¶

A one-way ANOVA test checks if there are significant differences in Sepal Length among the three species.

We perform a one-way ANOVA to test for differences in Sepal.Length among species. If the p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis that there are no significant differences.

In [ ]:
# 8. Conduct a one-way ANOVA to test if there are significant differences in Sepal.Length among the three species
print("\nConducting One-way ANOVA for Sepal.Length:")
f_stat, p_val = f_oneway(Iris[Iris['Species'] == 'setosa']['Sepal.Length'],
                         Iris[Iris['Species'] == 'versicolor']['Sepal.Length'],
                         Iris[Iris['Species'] == 'virginica']['Sepal.Length'])
print(f'F-statistic={f_stat}, p-value={p_val}')
if p_val < 0.05:
    print("There are significant differences in Sepal.Length among the species (reject H0)")
else:
    print("No significant differences in Sepal.Length among the species (fail to reject H0)")

Conducting One-way ANOVA for Sepal.Length:
F-statistic=119.26450218450468, p-value=1.6696691907693826e-31
There are significant differences in Sepal.Length among the species (reject H0)
In [ ]:
# OPTION 2
# One-way ANOVA to test for differences in Sepal.Length among species 
print("\nOne-way ANOVA...")
species = Iris['Species'].unique()
sepal_lengths = [Iris[Iris['Species'] == species]['Sepal.Length'] for species in species]
f_stat, p_val = f_oneway(*sepal_lengths)
print(f"F-statistic: {f_stat:.2f}, p-value: {p_val:.2f}")
if p_val < 0.05:
    print("Reject H0: There are significant differences in Sepal.Length among species")
else:
    print("Fail to reject H0: There are no significant differences in Sepal.Length among species")

One-way ANOVA...
F-statistic: 119.26, p-value: 0.00
Reject H0: There are significant differences in Sepal.Length among species

As seen, the p-value (1.67e-31) is significantly less than 0.05, leading to the rejection of the null hypothesis.

So, we conclude that there exists a significant difference in Sepal.Length among the three species of iris.

Post-hoc tests and Analysis:¶

Tukey's HSD test determines which pairs of species differ significantly in Sepal Length.

We use Tukey's HSD to perform post-hoc tests to determine which pairs of species differ significantly in Sepal.Length.

In [ ]:
# 9. Perform post-hoc tests to determine which pairs of species differ significantly in Sepal.Length
print("\nPerforming Post-hoc Tukey HSD Test:")
tukey_result = pairwise_tukeyhsd(Iris['Sepal.Length'], Iris['Species'])
print(tukey_result)

Performing Post-hoc Tukey HSD Test:

---------------------------------------------------------

In [ ]:
# Post-hoc tests using Tukey's HSD
print("\nPost-hoc tests...")
tukey = pairwise_tukeyhsd(endog=Iris['Sepal.Length'], groups=Iris['Species'], alpha=0.05)
print(tukey)

Post-hoc tests...
   Multiple Comparison of Means - Tukey HSD, FWER=0.05   
=========================================================
  group1     group2   meandiff p-adj lower  upper  reject
---------------------------------------------------------
    setosa versicolor     0.93   0.0 0.6862 1.1738   True
    setosa  virginica    1.582   0.0 1.3382 1.8258   True
versicolor  virginica    0.652   0.0 0.4082 0.8958   True
---------------------------------------------------------

After reviewing the results ffrom the Tukey HSD test, we see that there are differences in Sepal.Length between all pairs of species.

Secondly, the p-values for all comparisons are verry small (0.0), which pushes us to the rejection of null hypothesis for each pair. This indicates that the mean Sepal.Length differs significantly across all pairs of species.
